st the armed services take advantage of the plethora of commercial launches by sending their own communications payloads into orbit as hosted payloads**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. To promote the idea, the Hosted Payload Alliance was established in March by Boeing Space and Intelligence Systems, Intelsat General Corp., Iridium Communications Inc., Lockheed Martin Space Systems, Orbital Sciences Corp., SES World Skies U.S. Government Solutions and Space Systems/Loral. </span>__The U.S. Army’s 2010 test of an Internet router in orbit is likely to pave the way for more hosted payloads__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">, industry officials said. The Cisco-supplied Internet Routing in Space device, called ISIS, was launched as a payload on the Intelsat 14 satellite. “We think </span>__that’s a great model__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">,” said Philip Harlow, president and chief operating officer of satellite service provider Xtar LLC of Rockville, Md. If the primary payload does not tap out the satellite’s weight and power requirements, a secondary payload can benefit by paying a fraction of the cost of a dedicated spacecraft, Harlow added. Demand and supply </span>__Officials on all sides are certain there is no going back to a situation in which the military satisfies its own demand__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. Before the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the U.S. military’s own satellites supplied 80 percent of the bandwidth used by U.S. forces. </span>__Now, 80 percent of the communications are supplied by commercial satellites__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. In 2009, the U.S. communications director in Iraq told attendees at a satellite conference that </span>__96 percent of the communications requirements of U.S. Central Command__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> were being handled by commercial satellites. </span>**__The U.S. government’s current demand for an estimated 20 gigabytes per second of bandwidth is approximately twice the amount currently available__**<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">, said Craig Cooning, chairman of Boeing Space and Intelligence Systems, at the Satellite 2011 conference in Washington. “</span>**__By 2019, the demand will reach 50 gigabytes per second__**__, and only 60 percent of that will be met__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">,” he added. “</span>**__The military appetite for bandwidth will never decrease, even after we draw down in the Middle East__**<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">,” Weston said. Industry already is responding to consumer and government demand by launching new satellites and offering new services. London-based Inmarsat, Hughes Communications, Yahsat of the United Arab Emirates, Iridium Communications, Paris-based Eutelsat and ViaSat Inc. are investing billions of dollars in new Ka-band satellites that promise lightning-quick data transmission rates. Competitors warn that Ka-band service can be degraded by dust and rain, but government and industry officials said the benefits of high data throughput combined with smaller antenna sizes will make both military and commercial Ka-band an important component of any future satellite communications network. Planning would be required for U.S. forces to make seamless use of military and commercial Ka-band because private companies and the military rely on different Ka-band ranges. The military uses 20.2 gigahertz to 21.2 gigahertz as the downlink frequency for Ka-band communications, and 30 to 31 gigahertz as the uplink frequencies bands. Commercial satellites use 17.7 to 20.2 gigahertz for the downlink and 27.5 to 30 gigahertz for the uplink. The Defense Department’s Wideband Global Satcom, which provides services to military users for free, transmits data in the military Ka-band and also X-band frequencies. Right now, military agencies do not have any ground terminals designed to operate in both the commercial and military Ka-band frequencies, but service officials are considering purchasing 