e systems, including: The Big Picture Speed to Deployment Technical Attributes Technical Concerns Easy Retrofit or Large-scale Re-engineering The Bottom Line The Big Picture The military business, specifically the U.S. Military, has been a stable and growing vertical market over at least the past seven years, in particular since the Iraq war. Satellite operators and service providers have spun-off government entities specifically to serve military and government customers more efficiently, and these divisions account for a growing revenue stream with little sign of slowing down. Increased military bandwidth requirements over the long term lead to a question of deploying more satellite capacity in order to support a relatively stable business, yet satellite operators have not taken risks even when the Pentagon has indicated that it cannot be selfreliant until at least the year 2020. The move is understandable given that longer term military contracts are hard to come by, unlike the video markets where transponder capacity is signed over the long term. On the military side, a seemingly growing bandwidth crunch has led to plans to increase deployment of proprietary satellite assets, which cost in the $billions. Programs such as Wideband Gapfiller Satellite (WGS), Advanced Extremely High Frequency (AEHF) and the Transformational Satellite Communications System (TSAT) have been slated as budget line items to specifically address the growing bandwidth needs of the U.S. Military. However, budget processes are oftentimes arduous and protracted in justifying procurement of such assets, particularly during times when governments are faced with other seemingly more pressing issues such as financial bailouts in order to restore the health of their economy, if not the entire global financial system. Budget Considerations in Light of the Current State of the Global Economy Consequences of budget processes inherent in government procurement often lead to delays of programs, reduction of the original capability of programs, or the outright cancellation of such programs. However, as requirements for war fighting that inherently incorporate next-generation systems like communications-on-the-move (COTM) capabilities need to become more integrated in a defense network umbrella, delays, cutbacks or cancellations impede or even handicap a nation’s ability to project power. The current state of the global economy certainly puts into question many priorities in terms of civil needs and military needs. On balance, as a new administration takes the reigns of power in the United States, it puts priorities in serving America’s needs while protecting the safety and interests of its citizens at home and abroad. Spending for civil priorities at home such as a jobs creation program that address immediate needs will likely take precedence over next-generation military programs. Bandwidth requirements for the U.S. Military may seem a minor consideration as funds for bank and auto industry bailouts among others are debated in the U.S. Congress. The scale as well as the priority by which other industries is put ahead of programs including military resource build-up leads to alternative thinking that should address both budget savings and resource improvement in light of the current economic turmoil the U.S. and the globe has to undergo within the next year or two. An idea that has been regularly discussed in light of budget considerations is to host a government or military payload on a commercial satellite. Dual-use programs for use by both commercial and government clients have actually been in existence and have worked quite well for other governments like Australia and South Korea. Will hosted payloads or dual-use satellite systems work just as well for the U.S. Military, the largest government entity that uses commercial satellite bandwidth? And will other nations continue to practice hosted payload arrangements or will their own technical requirements lead to proprietary satellite program deployment as well? Military and Government demand for Commercial Satellite Services </span>**__Reliance on commercial satellite assets is now a foregone conclusion__** __and will remain a key component of U.S. and international government/military strategies for the foreseeable future__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. Commercial satellite operators, specifically Intelsat, Eutelsat and SES Global, have accounted for a large percentage of U.S. Military leases and their government arms see continued growth in both transponder uptake and revenue streams for services over the near term. But as mentioned earlier, even with admission from the Pentagon that a bandwidth gap exists and is likely growing, Intelsat, Eutelsat and SES have not disclosed plans to launch satellites over the globe’s hotspots like Iraq and Afghanistan. Once again, government procurement as seen historically is unlike video customers that sign leases over the long term. Interviews by NSR with these operators point to the fact that </span>**__the U.S. Government seems to be more open to a closer partnership. Whether these discussions lead to long term leases__** __capacity on **or to** **put payloads on commercial satellites will depend on contract vehicles over the next few years**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. It is quite apparent from the U.S. Department of Defense (DoD) itself that </span>**__even with the launch of its own proprietary assets, net-centric warfare will require bandwidth that is at least twice the capability of the WGS constellation__**__. An inflection point in 2010__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> (see curve above) </span>__is foreseen by the Pentagon where **a sudden surge of demand from less than 20 [gigabytes per second]** Gbps **of capacity surges to over 30** Gbps of demand **by 2012, jumping** further **to** approach **50** Gbps **by 2019**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. </span>**__Currently, the Pentagon’s answer to its bandwidth shortfall is to outsource what it needs to commercial satellite operators__**<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. The DoD has outlined commercial bandwidth needs by frequency and by region of the globe until 2019 [2]. Historically, </span>__the largest cost of commercial outsourcing__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> as seen in Figure 3 </span>__to the U.S. Military has been bandwidth, accounting for 87% of all spending__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> form 2000-2005. The next line item, </span>__equipment purchases, account for a mere 4% of total spending__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. In its own projections, NSR adheres to the U.S. Military’s view that indeed, the Pentagon will have little choice but to outsource capacity to commercial operators [1]. However, the launch of new internal capacity should have some effect on commercial demand such that developments in equipment and frequency will have to move form commercial to proprietary developments. Moreover, the call for withdrawal of troops in Iraq as well as the budget crunch in the U.S. should further lead to decreasing commercial bandwidth demand in the near term. Commercial capacity demand by the U.S. Military should diminish but not disappear. The commercial market in terms of bandwidth demand has likely peaked in 2008 and will likely begin to decline until 2014 before growing at positive levels once again beginning in 2015. Militaries and civil government agencies have outsourced bandwidth requirements on traditional commercial C-band and Ku-band transponders, as well as X-band that fall under the exclusive use of non-commercial customers. In the future, commercial Ka-band transponders are expected to be used more extensively by government customers as well. The growth of commercially outsourced bandwidth has been steady since 2003 for both U.S. and non-U.S. government users. As applications and communications requirements grow over time and commercially outsourced bandwidth begin to be integrated more fully in Netcentric warfare, security requirements that may not be at the level that the U.S. Military may be used to have to be addressed. And therein lies one of the challenges of incorporating commercial capacity that puts into question whether it is indeed compelling to dual-use or hosted payload solutions as a sound and/or viable option for the U.S. and other military entities around the globe. Issues with Hosted Payloads Militaries have invested on highly expensive systems and paid very high premiums due to requirements that are oftentimes not met by commercial bandwidth resources. Uppermost in the minds of military users are the following requirements. • Security • Reliability • Availability • Cost The current and planned resources of the U.S. Military have the following attributes: • Defense Satellite Communications System DSCS satellites use super-high frequencies for secure, jam-proof voice and data communications among defense officials, battlefield commanders, ground troops, aircraft, ships, the White House and the State Department. They also carry space operations communications and early warning data. • Wideband Gapfiller Satellite (WGS), the replacement to DSCS, provides greater capability and bandwidth than all the DSCS satellites combined while keeping security and other features intact for X-band and Ka-band. • The constellation of Milstar satellites provide secure, jam resistant, worldwide communications in EHF, linking command authorities with ships, submarines, aircraft and ground stations. Milstars are the most secure of the various communications satellites. They resist jamming and are hardened against nuclear attack. Milstars can operate in any combat environment with a low probability of detection or interception. • The AEHF constellation is the successor to Milstar. The physics of the AEHF waveform make the satellites well suited for strategic communications in a nuclear stressed environment. The tight beam is