es around the globe. However, </span>__there are two issues that have haunted military procurement that__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> once again </span>__favor the case for hosted payloads__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. - </span>__Speed to Deployment: The schedule for deploying next-generation assets **has been delayed, which led to commercial outsourcing** in terms **of bandwidth** needs for Iraq and Afghanistan. Continued activities in these countries will likely put pressure on commercially available capacity covering these two countries. More importantly, **another flashpoint** around the globe such as a new hotspot **in the Middle East, South Asia or the Horn of Africa will strain available commercial bandwidth sources further**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. - </span>__Cost and Funding issues: As mentioned earlier, **cost and funding issues** continue to haunt next-generation satellite deployment__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. TSAT has been a victim of budget cuts where the constellation was originally planned or scheduled to be launched around the 2012-2014 period but has now been postponed for 2019. It is thus easy to speculate that the program may ultimately be cancelled due to funding shortfalls. In a more recent development, it was announced earlier this year that </span>__technical issues encountered during testing__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> and the need to swap out some faulty components </span>**__have delayed__** __the U.S. Air Force's first **AEHF** satellite and added some $259 million to the program's overall cost__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. The AEHF program's cost grew significantly in 2008 after Congress, concerned about the Air Force's ability to deliver TSAT on schedule, directed the service to buy a fourth satellite in the series. Although the third AEHF satellite was expected to cost $939 million, restarting production to build the fourth will cost $2.6 billion, according to a Sept. 30, 2008 Pentagon acquisition cost summary [3]. The addition of the fourth satellite brought the total estimated cost of the AEHF program to $9.9 billion, triggering a mandatory recertification of the program by the Pentagon. The Figure 5 above and 6 below shows the aggregate total capacity from programs such as WGS, MUOS, AEHF and TSAT, among many more that are currently expected to enter into service in the next six years [1]. This information comes from various official and historical data sources and U.S. and international programs manufacturer contacted by NSR. The figures above show a large addition of capacity for proprietary systems around the globe. This is dominated by the U.S. Military with the launch of WGS, MUOS, and AEHF and included in the chart is TSAT as well, although the TSAT program may be rescheduled or cancelled. Host government/military payloads on commercial satellites – a recap In 2003, the Optus and Defense C1 satellite was launched, carrying a mixed payload that now serves the needs of Singtel Optus Pty Limited and the Australian Department of Defense for Australia, New Zealand and East Asia. The satellite operates in four frequency bands: • Commercial services in Ku-band for Singtel Optus • Military communications at UHF, X-band and Ka-band for the Australian Department of Defense. Optus uses C1's Ku-band payload to distribute video, DTH, telephony and Internet connections to remote areas. For the Australian Department of Defense, the satellite's Kaband payload provides high-data rate broadcast coverage for video, voice and data communications. The satellite’s X-band provides medium-to-high data rate voice and data for land and maritime applications. And finally, the UHF payload provides secure low-rate voice and data communications to mobile platforms. In Asia, South Korea launched its first civil-military dual-use communication satellite in August 2006, a move that introduced cutting-edge warfare systems in its overall capability. The dual-use satellite carries 12 military relay terminals and 24 commercial terminals, whereby the 12 military relays are capable of covering troop communications from the Malacca Strait to the Central Pacific sea areas. Prior to the satellite’s launch, the South Korean military relied on ground-based communication systems; however, the system using underground military cables or microwave relay towers was vulnerable to enemy attack. The dual-use satellite system has been successful thus far such that South Korea plans to deploy a total of 20 satellites, including eight multipurpose satellites, by 2015 [Koreasat]. One of the key benefits of dual use systems include reduced costs compared to internal asset build-up. A case in point is the recent budget challenges faced by the U.S. Military’s TSAT program, which took a serious hit in FY2009. This will have a dramatic impact on U.S. Military capabilities as the bandwidth the U.S. had planned on owning internally will be drastically reduced within the time frame set forth in the original schedule of the program. Dual-use systems or </span>**__hosted payloads__** __that also draw on commercial customers **cost a fraction of proprietary assets**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. To illustrate, U.S. Military procurement of military satellites costs run in the billions of US dollars, while hosted payloads or dual-use satellites such as Australia’s Optus and Defense C1 cost $500 million. Even with payload and bus enhancements, where the costs of which are shared with the commercial operator or partner, the total price tag is far below deploying and owning a proprietary military system. </span>__The other benefit of dual use or hosted payloads is the speed by which assets are deployed. Even if TSAT were to be deployed based on the original scope of five satellites, the delays that are now expected to take place, where first launch has been moved from 2013 to 2016 at the earliest, means that bandwidth planning and systems capability will have to likewise be delayed. Barring other available alternatives, commercial outsourcing will once again have to take up the slack__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. These considerations appear to be in full view of the U.S. Military’s system planners. In July 2008, AGS (the U.S. government services affiliate of SES Global) announced that it was awarded a contract by the U.S. Air Force to host an experimental sensor on board a commercial spacecraft. The three-year $65 million firm fixed price contract will host the experimental sensor on board an SES AMERICOM spacecraft scheduled to be launched in 2010 and will operate over the United States. The program, known as the Commercially Hosted Infrared Payload (CHIRP) Flight Demonstration Program, will have the primary purpose of testing a new type of infrared sensor from geo-synchronous altitude. The passive infrared sensor will be integrated onto a commercial satellite so that it can be launched into orbit, and the data can then be transmitted to the ground for analysis. Although the CHIRP program is for experimental purposes only and also not designed to address the communications mission and bandwidth shortfall faced by the U.S. Military, </span>__one cannot help but ponder whether the next line of contracts coming from the U.S. Government will be for dual use satellites__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> similar to the Australia and South Korean models </span>__or for hosted payloads__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. It seems that the move is catching on as the 2009 Budget Request of the US. Navy included $42M over the next two years for a UHF satcom hosted payload to serve as an interim while the transition from the Ultra High Frequency Operational satellite (UFO) to the MUOS constellations take place. This would be a small prototype UHF payload to be outfitted as a secondary payload on an existing commercial spacecraft design. The Request for Proposal has been issued and the launch is expected in 2011 after a selection in late 2009. The impetus is there, having granted a contract to SES and discussions are more prevalent from both the military side as well as the commercial operator side. For the military, cost and speed provide compelling arguments to deploy a dual-use or hosted payload satellite system. For commercial satellite operators, cost-sharing, long-term contracting and an anchored tenant provide invaluable benefits in a business that is inherently risky given the 15-year life of the asset. This may mean that new and innovative procurements to provide capacity to bridge military customers needs is becoming a recognized acquisition procedure. However, technical concerns will still have to be addressed in order to ensure full reliability of the system. These issues and concerns include: Technical Attributes • Frequency coordination issues • Interference issues • Performance issues Technical Concerns • On the commercial operator side, will the hosted payload interfere with the operation of the satellite? • On the military side, will the commercial payload limit the performance of the military hosted payload? • Will the military customer accept that a commercial operator, with a larger stake in-orbit on the same platform take precedence and control over the satellite, hence its payload? Easy Retrofit or Large-scale Re-engineering • From a satellite manufacturer’s point of view, is a hosted payload system where the U.S. Military will have high technical requirements lead to wide-scale system’s development? • Will delivery time be impacted by the military payload? The Bottom Line In 2008, </span>__Pentagon leaders disclosed that non-traditional conflicts such as the insurgents and terrorists facing coalition forces in Iraq and Afghanistan will be the main military battlefields for years to come. The classified Pentagon assessment likewise concluded that **the U.S. Military in**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;"> many respects including </span>**__its__** __**bandwidth resources** **is prevented from improving its ability to respond to any new crisis such as potential outbreaks in North Korea, Iran, Lebanon or China**__<span style="font-size: 9.33333px;">. </span>**__Hosted payloads provide__** __a vehicle by which **cost savings and speed of deployment** are enabled by the commercial sector. Faced with the difficult current economic environment and the limited ability of the U.S. Government to allocate funds for next-generation space programs, hosted payloads may be the answer in **addressing urgent requirements in order to maintain and even improve its war fighting capability in terms of fully developing** “**Netcentricity**.”__

