nergy Mikhaylov—would be consistent with Russia’s increasing reliance on nuclear weapons to deter conventional as well as nuclear aggression. . . .”42 Russian Nuclear Testing After the Testing Moratorium Russia may still be conducting yield producing nuclear tests. In January 1999 Lev Ryabev, then-head of the Nuclear Energy Ministry’s Nuclear Munitions Development and Testing Department, said that so-called “subcritical” tests produce very small nuclear yield (i.e., 0.1 gram).43 The Russian press reported that PresidentYeltsin’s April 29, 1999 decree on nuclear weapons approved “hydronuclear field experiments.”44 Hydronuclear tests are designed to produce measurable nuclear yields and are inconsistent with a zero yield Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) or a zero yield moratorium. It is interesting that then-Russian First Deputy Minister for Nuclear Energy Viktor Mikhaylov wrote on April 29, 1999 about the importance of hydronuclear testing to maintaining the nuclear arsenal. He stated: “No state will be able to create nuclear weapons for the first time based solely on hydronuclear experiments. . . . But developed traditional nuclear powers can use hydronuclear experiments to perform tasks of improving reliability of their nuclear arsenal and effectively steward its operation. All countries indirectly gain here inasmuch as the risk of nuclear accidents is lowered . . . . Determining the limits of ‘authorized activity’ is no simple process and only professionals can direct it correctly.”45 In July 2001, Mikhaylov again stated that, “. . . the developed, traditional nuclear powers, using hydronuclear experiments, can perform the task of improving reliability of the nuclear arsenal and effectively track its operation while reducing the risk of possible accident.”46 These reports have high credibility. Numerous declassified, but unfortunately heavily redacted, Clinton administration CIA intelligence reports discussed possible Russian nuclear testing and whether it was