et Union, when it deployed missiles in Cuba, prompted the Caribbean crisis.”54 One wonders what he would be doing if the United States did not have a nuclear deterrent. In perhaps the most militant statement in the history of the Russian Federation, General Baluyevskiy in January 2008 stated that “We do not intend to attack anyone. But all our partners must realize that for the protection of Russia and its allies, if necessary, the Armed Forces will be used, including preventively and with the use of nuclear weapons.”55 China’s Strategic Nuclear Buildup Communist China is rapidly building up its military forces in preparation for an attack on Taiwan on the assumption that it will have to fight the United States. China’s objectives go beyond this. The People’s Republic of China (PRC) reportedly suggested to U.S. Pacific Command (PACOM) Commander Adm. Timothy Keating that the Pacific be divided into spheres of influence.56 The official Chinese position is that it will suppress Taiwanese independence “at any cost”57 (emphasis added) which is understood to mean nuclear war.58 A 2003 Rand study concluded that, “the Chinese nuclear threat to the United States could evolve into a smaller version of the former Soviet Union.” 59 The November 2006 report of the Congressional U.S.-China Economic and Security Review Commission noted that “China continues to make significant strides in modernizing and enlarging its missile forces. Currently there are at least 10 types of ballistic missile systems that are either operational or under development.”60 The comparable number for the United States is two, with no new strategic missile under development. There are numerous press reports that China will MIRV its strategic missiles. A May 2007 report on the Hong Kong press stated that “The JL-2 series missile currently has three models; i.e. the JL-2, JL-2I, JL-2II” and that “the submarine can fire 48 warheads—each carrying the bomb equivalent of tens of thousands of tons—at 48 primary targets, which is sufficient to inflict heavy losses in a large country.”61 There are many press reports coming out of Hong Kong of plans to MIRV the new ballistic missiles it is producing (DF-31, DF-31A, and the JL-2) and that as many as 576 nuclear warheads will be deployed on the Chinese missile submarine fleet which is only one leg of the PRC’s nuclear TRIAD.62 A December 2000 Indian press report, attributed to Indian intelligence, reported that Chinese scientists were modifying a ‘bus’ to “carry about eight small nuclear warheads.”63 On six submarines, this adds up to 576 warheads. Chinese Nuclear Weapons Modernization There is no similarity between the post-ColdWar U.S. “stockpile stewardship” program and Chinese nuclear weapons development. China conducted nuclear tests after the 1992 moratorium and is dramatically improving its nuclear weapons.64 Yu Min, described by Xinhua as the “architect of the country’s first H-bomb,” claims that China’s key nuclear capabilities are “on a par with the United States and the former Soviet Union.”65 Xue Bencheng, one of the most important scientists involved in the development of China’s neutron bomb, stated that the July 1996 Chinese nuclear test was “a great spanning leap” because it solved the problem of nuclear weapons miniaturization.66 China’s Central Military Commission Vice Chairman Zhan Wannian told the Commission that there will be “further upgrading, and further development [of Chinese nuclear weapons] from 2001 to 2009.”67 The 2005 Pentagon report on Chinese military power observed that, “Some People’s Liberation Army (PLA) theorists . . . might consider using high-attitude electromagnetic pulses (HEMP) in an unconventional attack, believing that the United States and other nations would not consider it as a use of force and a crossing of the nuclear threshold.”68 China’s nuclear weapons development has clearly benefited from espionage against the U.S. The House Select Committee on U.S. National Security and Mil